
USE CASE DRAFT: T1110 - Brute Force



ATTACK DESCRIPTION
Adversaries systematically guess passwords or encryption keys using repetitive or iterative mechanisms. Attackers use this approah to gain initial access, escalata priveleges, or move laterally(machine to machine till they find a vulnerability) wihtin a compromised environment.


ATT&CK Mapping
Technique ID: T1110
Technique name: Brute Force

Tactics:
- Initial Access(TA0001), the adversary is trying to get into your network
- Stealth(TA0005), the adversary is trying to conceal their acitons, appearing as normal behavior
- Impact(TA0040), the adversary is trying to manipulate, interrupt, or destroy your systems.

Detection Objective
Pinpoint accounts experiencing an unusually large amount of failed authentication attempts within a short period of time

Potential Data Sources
Windows Security Logs - Event ID 4625(records a failed logon attempt), Event ID 4624(records eveyr succesful logon attempt), Event ID 4648(process succesfully attempted to logon to account by explicitly specifying account's credentials)

Detection Idea
- Monitor failed authenticaiton attempts and identify accounts generating an excessive number of login failures within a detailed time period

Examples of suspicious behavior:
- PASSWORD SPRAYING - one source's IP attempts a common password among many accounts
- One account recieves dozens-hundreds of failed logon attempts
- Distributed attacks may originate from several IP addresses attempting to compromise a single account

Investigation commands:
Find failed logons for users --> check for successful login after failures --> Identify Source IPs --> Determine Affected Systems -- > Find Accounts being targeted

Alert Concept

Alert name: Excessive Failed Logon Attempts Detected
Trigger Condition: More than 10 failed logins, Within 5 mintues, Against a single account
Severity: Medium --> Escalate to High if a priveleged account is targeted, multiple accounts are affected, or a successful login(4624) follows the failures

